00:50:12.400 --> 00:50:13.858
look for, and words
that you should

00:50:13.858 --> 00:50:15.620
look for on the packaging.

00:50:15.620 --> 00:50:18.214
And one thing that I
learned during the research

00:50:18.214 --> 00:50:20.130
for this book is, you
know the little stickers

00:50:20.130 --> 00:50:22.590
that you see on the produce
at the grocery store?

00:50:22.590 --> 00:50:27.720
It's called a PLU sticker,
which is a price look up code.

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:30.720
And basically any sticker that
you see that starts with a 4--

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:33.180
so it'll be like,
4695-- anything

00:50:33.180 --> 00:50:36.800
that starts with a number
4 is commercially grown.

00:50:36.800 --> 00:50:39.830
So that means that
they do use pesticides,

00:50:39.830 --> 00:50:43.040
and you don't exactly
know what's on it.

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:46.030
And so in order to reduce
your pesticide intake when

00:50:46.030 --> 00:50:48.080
you buy commercially
grown produce--

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:51.620
because I can't always afford
to buy everything organic--

00:50:51.620 --> 00:50:53.930
but the things that I
buy commercially grown,

00:50:53.930 --> 00:50:58.877
I'm sure to peel or scrub
really well, wash really well.

00:50:58.877 --> 00:51:00.960
So that's how you know if
it's commercially grown.

00:51:00.960 --> 00:51:03.660
And if you see a number
9 starting the number,

00:51:03.660 --> 00:51:05.450
that means that it's organic.

00:51:05.450 --> 00:51:07.194
So that's a fun,
little tip for you when

00:51:07.194 --> 00:51:08.360
you're at the grocery store.

00:51:08.360 --> 00:51:09.490
You can check it
out and make sure

00:51:09.490 --> 00:51:10.906
that things are
in the right bins.

00:51:10.906 --> 00:51:13.600
Because sometimes like,
what kind of apple is this?

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:16.280
It's a little confusing.

00:51:16.280 --> 00:51:18.450
So thanks, that's a good point.

00:51:18.450 --> 00:51:20.550
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering if we wanted

00:51:20.550 --> 00:51:23.050
to create our own
weekly plan, do

00:51:23.050 --> 00:51:26.710
you have a suggestion for
a strategy for planning

00:51:26.710 --> 00:51:29.110
those such that you use
up all the ingredients?

00:51:29.110 --> 00:51:32.340
Because I do plan my
meals, but I'm really

00:51:32.340 --> 00:51:34.614
terrible at using everything.

00:51:34.614 --> 00:51:36.030
So I was just
wondering if you had

00:51:36.030 --> 00:51:38.420
a general strategy when you'
were putting those together.

00:51:38.420 --> 00:51:40.920
MALIA DELL: I love to hear that
you're making your own weeks

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:42.390
because that's awesome.

00:51:42.390 --> 00:51:44.720
I guess I would say
you can do it two ways.

00:51:44.720 --> 00:51:46.780
You could probably
start from whatever

00:51:46.780 --> 00:51:50.650
your favorite ingredients are
that you use across the board.

00:51:50.650 --> 00:51:54.800
So say, for example,
you love potatoes.

00:51:54.800 --> 00:51:59.720
And then I would find a bunch
of recipes that use potatoes,

00:51:59.720 --> 00:52:01.600
and kind of build
out from that so

00:52:01.600 --> 00:52:04.820
that I knew that I could use
it up in multiple things.

00:52:04.820 --> 00:52:06.530
So you could start
with the ingredient

00:52:06.530 --> 00:52:09.240
and build out a
shopping list from that.

00:52:09.240 --> 00:52:12.970
Or you could start off
with recipes that you like.

00:52:12.970 --> 00:52:18.022
And then read the lists on the
recipes, and say, OK, well,

00:52:18.022 --> 00:52:19.980
it says that I need this
many peppers for this,

00:52:19.980 --> 00:52:21.620
I need this many
peppers for this one.

00:52:21.620 --> 00:52:24.610
OK, so I need to buy four
peppers for this whole week.

00:52:24.610 --> 00:52:28.300
But my biggest recommendation is
prepping that food in advance.

00:52:28.300 --> 00:52:30.700
That's going to save you so
much time during the week.

00:52:30.700 --> 00:52:32.540
You're not going to want
to do it during the week,

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:33.560
and that's the sad part.

00:52:33.560 --> 00:52:35.480
It's like, we buy
all these ingredients

00:52:35.480 --> 00:52:39.190
with great intentions, like, I'm
going to cook this cauliflower.

00:52:39.190 --> 00:52:40.967
And then during the
week, you look at it,

00:52:40.967 --> 00:52:43.300
and you're just like, yeah,
I have no food in my fridge.

00:52:43.300 --> 00:52:44.670
I'm going to order takeout.

00:52:44.670 --> 00:52:48.220
So it's really having a plan,
and prepping it in advance

00:52:48.220 --> 00:52:50.357
so that you're more
likely to use it.

